Introduction

Blockchain is a decentralized digital ledger that securely records transactions across multiple computers. It ensures that data cannot be altered without the agreement of the network, making it transparent, secure, and trustworthy.

What is Blockchain?

A blockchain is a chain of blocks where each block stores:

Transaction data
Timestamp
Hash of the current block
Hash of the previous block

Because each block contains the previous block's hash, changing one block changes all subsequent hashes, making tampering extremely difficult.

Key Features
Decentralization: No central authority controls the network.
Transparency: Transactions are visible to all participants.
Security: Cryptography protects the data.
Immutability: Recorded data cannot be changed easily.
Consensus: Network participants agree on the validity of transactions.
Types of Blockchain
Public Blockchain
Open to everyone.
Anyone can participate.
Example: Ethereum, Bitcoin.
Private Blockchain
Controlled by a single organization.
Restricted access.
Example: Hyperledger Fabric.
Consortium Blockchain
Managed by multiple organizations.
Used by businesses for collaboration.
What is Ethereum?

Ethereum is a decentralized blockchain platform that supports smart contracts and decentralized applications (DApps).

Unlike Bitcoin, which mainly transfers digital currency, Ethereum allows developers to build applications that run without intermediaries.

Ether (ETH)

Ether (ETH) is Ethereum's native cryptocurrency.

It is used for:

Paying transaction fees
Deploying smart contracts
Rewarding validators
Participating in decentralized finance (DeFi)
Smart Contracts

A smart contract is a self-executing program stored on the blockchain.

Advantages
Automatic execution
Secure
Transparent
No intermediaries
Tamper-resistant

Example applications:

Voting systems
Supply chain management
NFT marketplaces
Decentralized exchanges
Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM)

The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) executes smart contracts on Ethereum-compatible blockchains.

Responsibilities:

Executes smart contract bytecode
Maintains blockchain state
Ensures deterministic execution
Provides security and isolation

Many blockchains such as SecureChain AI, Polygon, BNB Chain, and Avalanche are EVM-compatible.

Solidity

Solidity is the programming language used for writing Ethereum smart contracts.

Example:

// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity ^0.8.18;

contract HelloWorld {
    string public message = "Hello World";
}
Gas

Gas is the fee required to execute transactions on Ethereum.

Gas depends on:

Contract complexity
Network congestion
Gas price

Gas prevents spam attacks and compensates validators.

Ethereum Accounts
Externally Owned Account (EOA)
Controlled by a private key.
Used by users.
Contract Account
Controlled by smart contract code.
Executes automatically.
Consensus Mechanism

Ethereum uses Proof of Stake (PoS).

Validators stake ETH to validate transactions and secure the network.

Benefits:

Lower energy consumption
Improved scalability
Better security
